{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}} {{about|the capital villages of Niue|the island, part of [[Wallis and Futuna]]|Alofi Island}} {{Infobox settlement |name = Alofi |settlement_type = [[List of villages in Niue|City]] |image_skyline = Alofi.jpg |image_alt = Alofi locals walking along a street |image_caption = Alofi Central |image_map = Alofi location map.png |mapsize = 250px |map_alt = |map_caption = Alofi council within Niue |image_map1 = Niue Verwaltungsgliederung.png |mapsize1 = 250px |map_alt1 = |map_caption1 = Administrative map of Niue showing all the villages. Alofi is on the western side of the island |coordinates = {{coord|-19.054|-169.920|region:NU_type:city(614)_dim:12000|display=inline,title}} |subdivision_type = Country |subdivision_name = {{flag|Niue}} |subdivision_type1 = Tribal Area |subdivision_name1 = [[Tafiti (tribal area)|Tafiti]] |subdivision_type2 = [[List of villages in Niue|Village]] |subdivision_name2 = [[Alofi North]] and [[Alofi South]] |leader_title = Assemblyman of Alofi North |leader_name = Vaiga Tukuitoga<ref name=MFAT>[[#MFAT|New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade]]</ref> |leader_title1 = Assemblyman of Alofi South |leader_name1 = Dalton Tagelagi<ref name=gov.nu>[[#gov.nu|Government of Niue]]</ref> |area_magnitude = 1 E+7 m² |area_blank1_title = Area of both Alofi North and Alofi South |area_blank1_km2 = 46.48 |area_blank1_sq_mi = |elevation_footnotes =<ref name=weather>[[#weather|Weatherbase]]</ref> |elevation_m = 21 |elevation_ft = |population_footnotes =<ref name="SPC2008-4">[[#SPC|SPC 2008]], p.4.</ref> |population_total = 1,000 |population_as_of = 2014 |population_density_km2 = 12.5 |population_density_sq_mi= 32.46 |population_blank1_title = Alofi North |population_blank1 = 147 |population_blank2_title = Alofi South |population_blank2 = 434 |demographics_type1 = Resident Population |demographics1_footnotes =<ref name="SPC2008-5">[[#SPC|SPC 2008]], p.5.</ref> |demographics1_title1 = Residents (Alofi North) |demographics1_info1 = |demographics1_title2 = Visitors (Alofi North) |demographics1_info2 = 6,214 |demographics1_title3 = Resident (Alofi South) |demographics1_info3 = |demographics1_title4 = Visitor (Alofi South) |demographics1_info4 = 6,214 |timezone1 = UTC-11 |utc_offset1 = -11 |area_code = [[Telephone numbers in Oceania|+683]] }} '''Alofi''' is the capital of the Pacific Ocean island nation of [[Niue]]. With a population of less than 1,000 (census of 2014){{needs citation|date=June 2017}}, Alofi has the distinction of being the second smallest national capital city in terms of population (after [[Ngerulmud]], capital of [[Palau]]). It consists of the two villages: '''Alofi North''' and '''Alofi South''' where the government headquarters are located.<ref name="SPC2008-4"/>
==History== In January 2004, Niue was hit by the fierce tropical storm [[Cyclone Heta]] which killed two people and did extensive damage to the entire island. Many of Alofi's buildings were destroyed, including the hospital. Government buildings were shifted to a less exposed site {{convert|3|km|abbr=on}} inland from the west coast, named '''Fonuakula''', after the storm.<ref name=heta>[[#heta|East-West Center]]</ref> This site is still within the village boundaries of Alofi South.
==Geography== ===Overview=== It is located at the centre of [[Alofi Bay]] on the west coast of the island, close to the only break in the [[coral reef]] that surrounds Niue. The bay stretches for 30% of the island's length (about seven kilometres) from [[Halagigie Point]] in the south to Makapu Point in the north.
The council's territory borders with [[Avatele]], [[Hakupu]], [[Lakepa]], [[Liku]], [[Makefu]], [[Mutalau]], [[Tamakautoga]] and [[Tuapa]].<ref>{{OSM|r|1558549|Alofi}}</ref>
===Climate=== {{climate chart | Alofi |23|28|260 |24|29|250 |24|28|300 |23|27|200 |22|26|130 |21|26|80 |20|25|90 |20|25|100 |21|26|100 |21|26|120 |22|27|140 |23|28|190 |float=left |source=Weatherbase<ref name="weather" /> }} Alofi features a [[tropical rainforest climate]] under the [[Köppen climate classification]], with no discernible [[dry season]]. The city has a noticeably drier stretch from June through September. However, all of these months average more than {{convert|60|mm|abbr=on}} of rain, the limit for a dry season month. Average temperatures vary slightly throughout the course of the year in Alofi hovering at around {{convert|27|C}}, during the warmest month (February) and at around {{convert|23|C}} during the coolest months (July and August) . {{clear left}}
==Transport== The town is serviced by [[Niue International Airport]], and there are numerous roads, both paved and dirt, that crisscross the town.<ref>[http://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?id=NE45256&sch=NIUE Niue International Airport]</ref>
==Personalities== *[[Dalton Tagelagi]] (b. 1968), politician *[[Sam Pata Emani Tagelagi]] (1935–2011), politician
